            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adam Singh\u2019s story begins not in Punjab, but in the manicured suburbs of Naperville, Illinois. Born Adam Miller to a single mother, his identity was reshaped at age nine when his mother married a kind, industrious software engineer named Raj Singh. Adam took his stepfather's name, a choice that brought stability and a subtle, lifelong sense of being slightly different in his homogenous Midwestern town. He grew up on a diet of diligence and pragmatism, excelling in school with a quiet, analytical mind.\n\nHe attended the University of Illinois for his Business Administration degree, recruited directly into a Chicago-based consulting firm upon graduation. Adam was a grinder, his ambition forged by a desire for the security his mother had struggled to provide. He survived the dot-com bust of the early 2000s by being indispensable, learning a crucial lesson about resilience that would define his career. In 2008, he saw an opportunity in the ashes of the financial crisis and moved to San Francisco, joining a boutique firm that helped tech companies scale and restructure.\n\nHis key turning point was making Partner five years ago. The culmination of two decades of grueling hours, it delivered the financial success he\u2019d long sought but coincided with the quiet end of a decade-long relationship. The long workdays had left little room for nurturing a personal life.\n\nNow, Adam\u2019s life is one of structured precision. He lives in a sleek Rincon Hill high-rise, his 1.1-mile walk to his Financial District office a cherished daily ritual. The walk is his meditation, a transition from his private space to the steel-and-glass canyon where he solves complex corporate problems. His social circle is tight, consisting mostly of other high-achieving professionals. Weekends are for runs along the Embarcadero and occasional trips to Napa to decompress.\n\nAt 49, Adam finds himself at an inflection point. He has achieved his financial dreams, but the summit feels solitary. He aspires to pivot, hoping to use his capital and expertise to mentor or invest in startups with a social conscience. He dreams of building something with lasting meaning beyond a balance sheet, and perhaps, finally finding a partnership that his demanding career can complement rather than consume."
